    tags: ['Optimization', 'Gradient Descent', 'Neural Networks', 'Training'],
    coverEmoji: '⚡',
    content: [
      { type: 'h2', text: 'Plain SGD: The Baseline' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Stochastic Gradient Descent updates weights by moving in the direction of negative gradient.' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Problem: Oscillations and Slow Convergence' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'In high-dimensional loss surfaces, gradients are noisy. Plain SGD zigzags inefficiently, especially in steep ravines.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'The Momentum Intuition' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Physics Analogy' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Like a ball rolling downhill: it builds up speed and momentum, smoothing out bumps. It does not stop at every obstacle.' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Mathematical Idea' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Plain SGD changes direction every step. Momentum continues previous direction while applying current gradient.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'How Momentum Works' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'The Algorithm' },
      { type: 'list', ordered: true, items: ['Initialize velocity = 0', 'For each batch: compute gradient', 'Update velocity = beta * velocity - learning_rate * gradient', 'Update weights: w = w + velocity', 'Repeat'] },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Key Parameters' },
      { type: 'list', ordered: false, items: ['beta (momentum coefficient): typically 0.9', 'learning_rate: step size (usually smaller than plain SGD)', 'velocity: accumulated direction, updated each step'] },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'Key Benefits of Momentum' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Benefit 1: Faster Convergence' },
      { type: 'list', ordered: false, items: ['Plain SGD takes many zigzag steps', 'Momentum accumulates speed in consistent direction', 'Empirical result: 2-3x faster convergence'] },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Benefit 2: Escape Shallow Local Minima' },
      { type: 'list', ordered: false, items: ['Small gradient near minimum → SGD gets stuck', 'Momentum velocity carries through shallow minima', 'Can escape to better solutions'] },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Benefit 3: Reduce Oscillations' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Loss landscapes have narrow ravines. Plain SGD bounces side-to-side. Momentum averages oscillations away, moving smoothly down ravine.' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Benefit 4: Handle Noisy Gradients' },
      { type: 'list', ordered: false, items: ['Stochastic mini-batch gradients are noisy', 'Velocity smooths noise by averaging', 'Cleaner, more stable convergence'] },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'When Momentum Helps Most' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Scenario 1: Deep Neural Networks' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Complex loss surfaces with ravines. Momentum excels at traversing them.' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Scenario 2: Small Learning Rates' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Small learning rate makes progress slow. Momentum accumulates updates, builds speed.' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Scenario 3: Noisy Gradient Estimates' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Mini-batch SGD with small batches. Momentum averages gradient noise over time.' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Scenario 4: Consistent Gradient Directions' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'If gradients point the same way for many steps, velocity accumulates and accelerates convergence.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'Momentum Variants' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Standard Momentum' },
      { type: 'list', ordered: false, items: ['velocity = beta * velocity - lr * gradient', 'w = w + velocity'] },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Nesterov Momentum' },
      { type: 'list', ordered: false, items: ['Lookahead variant: apply gradient at projected position', 'More responsive, faster convergence', 'Often best momentum variant'] },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'Hyperparameter Tuning' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Momentum (beta)' },
      { type: 'list', ordered: false, items: ['0.0 = no momentum (plain SGD)', '0.5-0.7 = mild momentum (responsive)', '0.9 = strong momentum (standard)', '0.99 = very strong (risk of overshooting)'] },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Learning Rate with Momentum' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Momentum increases effective step size. Can often use higher learning rate than plain SGD.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'SGD+Momentum vs Other Optimizers' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Adam Optimizer' },
      { type: 'list', ordered: false, items: ['Adaptive learning rates per parameter', 'Easier to tune (less learning rate fiddling)', 'Sometimes overshoots near minimum', 'Popular in practice, but SGD+momentum often generalizes better'] },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Recommendation' },
      { type: 'list', ordered: false, items: ['Start with Adam (faster baseline)', 'Optimize with SGD+momentum (better final models)', 'Fine-tune with Nesterov momentum (best performance)'] },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'Common Mistakes' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Mistake 1: Learning Rate Too High' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Momentum amplifies updates. High learning rate + momentum = divergence or bouncing.' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Mistake 2: Momentum Too High' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Momentum > 0.95 causes overshooting. Model oscillates around minimum.' },
      { type: 'h3', text: 'Mistake 3: Ignoring Learning Rate Schedules' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Learning rate should decay over time. Without decay, momentum keeps bouncing near minimum.' },
      { type: 'h2', text: 'Key Takeaway' },
      { type: 'divider' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'SGD with momentum accelerates convergence by accumulating velocity in consistent gradient directions. Typical benefits: 2-3x faster convergence, escapes local minima, reduces noise. Works best on deep networks, small learning rates, and noisy gradients. Standard momentum beta = 0.9. Requires careful learning rate tuning. For production models, often beats Adam due to better generalization.' }
    ]
